Starting off on a sad note, the author of MC Yumi finally succumbed to her cancer and passed away. Fortunately, she provided the entire plot to her illustrator who will take up her work, so we'll still get more MC Yumi, but depending on how extensive her notes were the English translation and correct military terminology could suffer.

Only the distant spring winds can clear them from my eyes.
To a warm garden filled with azaleas
You made bloom…
Take me there, lead me there...
Just kidding…
There are no fairy tales that are filled with only happiness,

but still, you know,
I want to go there…

I was able to solve
complicated equations without the help of anyone.
I thought it was only natural to do it alone,
so I never doubted my actions…
But this season will soon come to an end,
and only my shadow will give me company.

In a storm of flowers
And show me the way..
So I don’t get lost.
There are no perfect crystals created by miracles,
that’s why we, one by one,

and soon…

still has that empty space.
I never knew

The day I waited for without realizing
has already melted away with the snow and soon spring will come.
It will become clear water
and then…
It will make the Azalea bloom.
But even after the long winter is over,
I’ll always, always,
be in this sunlit room.

Behind the large aquarium walls an assortment of fishes were swimming, with some of the smaller fishes hiding in the algae.

Amongst them a large red fish with an elegant look to it was swimming about freely without fear.

Upon sighting the fish Yukinoshita observed "And there's this carefree fellow."

"This fish? It is quite big."

"Nowhere to go, unable to find a resting place.. hidden in the currents, being swept along and chasing after something, only to hit an invisible wall."

Yukinoshita reached her hand towards the glass wall but retracted it right before they touched.
As I glanced carefully to the side, Yukinoshita was staring blankly in front of her.

"Which fish are you talking about?"

Yukinoshita did not speak immediately but calmly exhaled before replying. "I was talking about myself."

After her answer, Yukinoshita wored an indiscernible lonely smile and touched the aquarium wall.

Yukinoshita's outstretched profile was seemingly being absorbed into the waters but obstructed by the glass walls from returning to her original place.

It was an ethereal sight, so transient as to disappear in the blink of an eye.

It seems like Yukino and Hachiman have switched places sort of from the beginning of the series. At first, Yukino had this attitude about helping people improve themselves (and she wanted to improve herself most of all). She's back in a mode that presumably she was in before the series began and has surrendered to Hachiman''s original way of thinking. Ironically Hachiman seems to have moved towards Yukino's original way of thinking as the series has progressed. He's not opposed to bettering yourself anymore.

>>128058280
paste [dot] ee/p/Cg3De

This is a word stats list of the entire HTML LN collection (328 txt files) using the latest version of JapaneseTextAnalysisTool. It has a fixed user dictionary so that character sequences like それは don't mess with the rating of simple words like それ. I cut off the listing once it hit words with fewer than 50 instances in order to reduce its size and hide jargon that perhaps only one book used. The HTML files were STRIPPED OF RUBY TEXT and general HTML tags before processing.

This is the best we're gonna get unless someone plugs a larger corpus into it or we get Kuromoji (statistical chain based morpheme splitter) support.
>>

>>128081105
Reminder (from Ixrec's grammar guide on second person pronouns)
>お前 (おまえ) you the default second-person pronoun (especially for males)
>君 (きみ) you more friendly than おまえ, implying that there is some sort of relationship
>貴方 (あなた) you a second-person pronoun used by females, sometimes used specifically to address her husband
>あんた you a more colloquial version of あなた without the strong connotations
>てめ you used primarily to express contempt of the subject. Also, attaching め to the end of any noun or pronoun conveys the same nuance of contempt.
>貴様 (きさま) you essentially a more formal version of てめ. In some contexts this does not convey contempt, but rather an expectation of humility or submission.
>お主 (おぬし) you a very old second-person pronoun
>>

It can mean either "also/but" (similar to でも) or be a quote. It's also used to elaborate reasons, especially when arguing or trying to convince the other person.

>>128088050 >>128088200 >>128088514
>>128087591
に当たって means "in the event of" or "when doing ~", etc. It doesn't specifically mean "prior to". Sometimes it can be translated as that, if only because it tends to be used for "instantaneous actions" in the sense of "in order to".

http://dictionary.goo.ne.jp/leaf/thsrs/17122/m0u/
>また、「において」「にあって」は、「明治時代」「調査の過程」のように時間的な幅のある語句を受けるのに対し、「にあたって」「に際し(て)」は、「閉会」「出発」のように瞬間的な変化や動作の始点・終点を示す語句を受けやすいという違いもある。
>>

That's the literal meaning of 当たる, it doesn't really have anything to do with the "in the event of" meaning.

>>128088738
>>128088163
と is a common conditional for linking repeating occurrences.

e.g., 家に帰って妻の顔を見ると、心がほっとする。

problems with your sentence:
俺は is not necessary
後時 makes no sense
帰った is a little strange, it's something that happens when you return home so it should use the nonpast
見える takes no object (it means "to be visible")
宥める isn't a terribly common word in this sort of situation
transitive verb doesn't make much sense as it's a natural response and not something you're forced to do
>>

Charlotte Anonymous 07/15/15(Wed)06:41:10 No.128077903   [Reply]▶
Ok Something doesn't add up.
>Her brother is experimented on until he loses his mind.
>She escapes the school/science lab
>She finds the "one person" who can help her (no Yu)
>The scientists put her brother into an asylum.
>She comes to visit him regularly

HOW THE FUCK IS IT SHE HASN'T BEEN RECAPTURED BY THE SCIENTISTS YET!? I mean If one of your tests subjects runs away and you've put her brother into an asylum, why not monitor him and wait for her to come visit him? I mean she can only make herself invisible to one person so a couple of guards would be enough to get her. It seems like a pretty strait forward way to get her.

Either
1. The Scientists are dumber than they appear
2. The person helping her is VERY powerful politically/militarily/corporately and is thus keeping the scientists at bay.
3. Or the scientists are very smart and are actually using her to identify more people with abilities and the person helping her is actually in league/controlled by them in the first place.
4. The writers of the anime put in a giant gaping plot hole by mistake.
